<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-04-20T11:16:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-04-20T11:16:00-05:00" n="345" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d345">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/568</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SFJ1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Stimson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-20T12:00:00-04:16">
                                        <hi rend="italic">April 20, 1917, noon</hi></date>. <lb/>
                                        [<hi rend="italic">Received 2.30 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Your April 19, 5 p.m. The proposed congress of American nations to be
                                called upon the initiative of Argentina to meet at Buenos Aires was
                                first called peace congress (see my February 27, 11 a.m., and March
                                3, 11 a.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d345fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_235">pp.
                                    235</ref>, <ref target="#pg_236">236</ref>.</note>), then called
                                only a commercial congress (see my March 3, noon,<note n="2" xml:id="d345fn2">Not printed.</note> your March 14, 6 p.m., my
                                March 16, 6 p.m., and my April 16, noon<note n="3" xml:id="d345fn3">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_240">pp.
                                    240</ref>, <ref target="#pg_241">241</ref>, <ref target="#pg_256">256</ref>.</note>), and now called
                                officially Congress of the Nations of America (see my April 17, 1
                                    p.m.<note n="4" xml:id="d345fn4">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_257">p.
                                    257</ref>.</note>). All of these telegrams refer to the same
                                subject.</p>
                            <p>The idea has been accepted so far by Bolivia, Brazil, Chile,
                                Colombia, Cuba, Mexico, Paraguay, and Peru but the invitations are
                                not yet issued.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SFJ1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>